## 1ï¸âƒ£5ï¸âƒ£ screen (Persistent Sessions)

### Commands

```bash
screen
screen -S mysession
screen -ls
screen -r mysession
screen -X -S mysession quit
```

### Explanation

* Keeps jobs running after logout.
* Older alternative to tmux.

---

## 1ï¸âƒ£6ï¸âƒ£ tmux (Modern Standard)

### Commands

```bash
tmux
tmux new -s devsession
tmux ls
tmux attach -t devsession
tmux kill-session -t devsession
```

### Explanation

* Persistent, multi-pane terminal.
* Widely used by DevOps.

---

## 1ï¸âƒ£7ï¸âƒ£ Signals & kill

### Commands

```bash
kill -l
kill PID
kill -9 PID
kill -HUP PID
```

### Explanation

* `SIGTERM (15)` â†’ graceful
* `SIGKILL (9)` â†’ force
* `SIGHUP (1)` â†’ reload

### Interview line

> â€œAlways try SIGTERM before SIGKILL.â€

---

## 1ï¸âƒ£8ï¸âƒ£ Right Way to Kill Process

### Steps

```bash
kill PID
sleep 5
kill -9 PID
```

### Explanation

* Avoids data corruption.
* Production-safe approach.

---

## 1ï¸âƒ£9ï¸âƒ£ Cleaning Zombie Processes

### Commands

```bash
ps aux | awk '$8~/Z/'
ps -o ppid= -p ZPID
kill -TERM PARENT_PID
```

### Explanation

* Zombies die only when parent exits.
* Killing zombie itself does nothing.

---

## 2ï¸âƒ£0ï¸âƒ£ pstree (Hierarchy View)

### Commands

```bash
pstree
pstree -p
pstree -a
pstree -h PID
```

### Explanation

* Visualizes parent-child relationships.
* Excellent for debugging.

---

## 2ï¸âƒ£1ï¸âƒ£ Process Groups & Sessions

### Commands

```bash
ps -eo pid,ppid,pgid,sid,cmd
kill -TERM -PGID
setsid command
```

### Explanation

* Group signals control multiple processes.
* Used in shells and daemons.

---

## 2ï¸âƒ£2ï¸âƒ£ nohup (Long-Running Jobs)

### Commands

```bash
nohup job.sh &
echo $! > job.pid
```

### Explanation

* Job survives logout.
* `$!` captures PID.

---

## 2ï¸âƒ£3ï¸âƒ£ Real Production Scenarios

### CPU hog

```bash
ps aux --sort=-%cpu
renice +10 PID
```

### Memory leak

```bash
watch ps -o pid,vsz,rss -p PID
```

### Runaway processes

```bash
